Crop Seedling Classification Project

Varun Kulkarni (kulkarnivarun@outlook.com)

Objective¶

Classify given plant seedling.

Context¶

Can you differentiate a weed from a crop seedling? The ability to do so effectively can mean better crop yields and better stewardship of the environment. The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 species at several growth stages.

Data Description¶

You are provided with a dataset of images of plant seedlings at various stages of grown. Each image has a filename that is its unique id. The dataset comprises 12 plant species. The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo

Dataset¶

The dataset can be download from Olympus. The data file names are:

  • images.npy
  • Label.csv

The original files are from Kaggle. Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to images.npy file and the labels are also put into the Labels.csv. So that you can work on the data/project seamlessly without worrying about the high data volume.

Tasks¶

  1. Import the libraries, load dataset, print shape of data, visualize the images in dataset.
  2. Data Pre-processing
  3. Data Preparation: Making data compatible
  4. Building CNN Model
  5. Training and Evaluating Model
  6. Visualize Predictions

#
# Visualize images in the dataset
#
def show_images(images, labels, grid_size=(3,4), width=18, height=10):
    ''' Method to visualize images 
    
    images    - Set of images to view
    labels    - Corresponding labels for images
    grid_size - (rows, columns) for subplots 
    width     - Width of the figure
    height    - height of the figure '''
    
    assert(len(images) == len(labels))

    # Grid to show images
    rows = grid_size[0]
    cols = grid_size[1]
    
    # Show image per class
    fig = plt.gcf()
    fig.set_size_inches(width, height)
    for idx, (img, lbl) in enumerate(zip(images, labels)):
        sp = plt.subplot(rows, cols, idx+1)
        sp.axis('Off')     
        plt.title(lbl)
        plt.imshow(img)
    

# Get classes in sorted order. 
# Note: The sorted order maintains compatibility with that of one-hot encoder 
# used later.
labels = sorted(labels_df['Label'].unique())

# Pick first index for each category
min_label_indexes = [min(labels_df[labels_df.Label == label].index) for label in labels]

# Pick sample images based on above indexes
images_to_show = [images[idx] for idx in min_label_indexes]

# Display images along with respective labels
show_images(images_to_show, labels)

Observations:¶

  • There are 4750 images each of dimension (128x128x3), height and width being 128 pixels and three color channels (RGB). The size of the images seems fine for further processing.
  • There are 12 categories of plant seedlings. The given dataset is inclined towards 'Loose Silky-bent', 'Common Chickweed' and 'Scentless Mayweed' in terms of number of samples/records.
  • 'Maize', 'Common wheat', and 'Shepherds Purse' have comparatively less samples. May be we should consider up sampling for these categories.
  • Upon careful observation it is seen that each seedling has a background that may not be useful while classifying the category of the seedling. Background objects such as pebbles, bar-codes, fine sand can contribute to noise in data. The background should be handled in some way.
  • Each plant seedling is green in color.

Data Pre-processing ¶

In [ ]:
#
# Let's define the algorithm for pre-processing images.
# The motivation is to hide/mask the background that may contribute to
# noise in the data. 
#
def process_image(img, return_intermediates=False):
    # Apply Gaussian Blur
    gblurImg = cv2.GaussianBlur(img, (5, 5), 0)
    
    # Let's remove the background

    # Convert to HSV color space
    hsvImg = cv2.cvtColor(gblurImg, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
    # HSV color space lower green values
    start_hsv_green = (24, 40, 40)
    # HSV color space upper green values
    end_hsv_green = (76, 255, 255)

    # Create mask to retain green regions
    mask = cv2.inRange(hsvImg, start_hsv_green, end_hsv_green)
    
    # Create boolean mask
    booleanMask = (mask > 0)
    
    # Apply the mask to retain the seedling and remove the background
    resultImg = np.zeros_like(img, np.uint8)
    resultImg[booleanMask] = img[booleanMask]
    
    # Return intermediate results if requested
    if return_intermediates:
        return [img, gblurImg, hsvImg, mask, booleanMask, resultImg]
    
    # Return final processed image
    return resultImg


# Let's look at the effects of pre-processing on a sample image
sample_img = images[0]

# Get all image transformations
transformations = process_image(sample_img, return_intermediates=True)

# Titles for transformations
tranform_titles = ['Original Image', 'Gaussian Blur', 'HSV Image', 'Image Mask', 
                   'Boolean Image Mask', 'Resultant Image']


# Show transformations on a sample image
show_images(transformations, tranform_titles, grid_size=(2,3), width=16, height=9)

  • This will help our model to not be impacted by the noise and extract features related to actual seedling.

Building CNN model ¶

In [ ]:
# Start with sequential model.
model = Sequential() 

# Define Feature Extractor

# First convolution layer with 32 filters and ReLU activation followed by MaxPooling
# This layer interfaces to the input of shape (128, 128, 3)
model.add(Conv2D(32, 3, strides=1, input_shape=(128, 128, 3), activation='relu')) 
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))

# Second convolution layer with 64 filters and ReLU activation followed by MaxPooling
model.add(Conv2D(64, 3, strides=1, activation='relu')) 
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))

# Third convolution layer with 128 filters and ReLU activation followed by MaxPooling
model.add(Conv2D(128, 3, strides=1, activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))

# Fourth convolution layer with 256 filters and ReLU activation followed by MaxPooling
model.add(Conv2D(256, 3, strides=1, activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))

# Classifier

# Flatten inputs with batch normalization
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(BatchNormalization())

# Add first fully connected layer with 64 neurons followed by batch normalization and ELU activation
model.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer='he_normal', use_bias=False))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Activation('elu'))

# Add second fully connected layer with 32 neurons followed by batch normalization and ELU activation
model.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer='he_normal', use_bias=False))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Activation('elu'))

# Add output layer for multi-class classification with softmax activation function
model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

# Create optimizer instance with slightly lower learning rate, as we have batch normalization to converge faster
opt = optimizers.Adam(lr=0.001)

# Configure the model with categorical cross entropy loss, the optimizer,
# and accuracy as the metrics
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=opt, metrics=['accuracy'])

# Print model summary
model.summary()

Training and Evaluating the Model ¶

In [ ]:
#
# Based on the observations while training, 90% accuracy on train and validation 
# data is fairly good. After that the model might overfit.
#
# Let's define a callback for early stopping based on both train and validation
# accuracies
#
class TerminateOverBaseline(Callback):
    '''Callback that terminates training when given prameters reach specified 
        baseline'''

    def __init__(self, monitor=[], baselines=[]):
        super(TerminateOverBaseline, self).__init__()
        self.monitor = monitor
        self.baselines = baselines

    def on_epoch_end(self, epoch, logs=None):
        logs = logs or {}
        results = []

        # Collect all required results from this epoch
        for mon in self.monitor:
            res = logs.get(mon)
            if res is None: return
            results.append(res)

        # Check if all of the results are above their respective specified baselines 
        assert len(results) == len(self.baselines)
        for r,b in zip(results, self.baselines):
            if r < b: return

        # Stop training
        self.model.stop_training = True
        print('\nEpoch {0} satisfied all baselines, terminating training.\n'.
              format(epoch))
        
# Create instance of the callback for train and validation accuracy of 91% baselines
callback = TerminateOverBaseline(monitor=['accuracy','val_accuracy'], 
                                 baselines=[0.90, 0.90])

# Define data generator for data augmentation and scaling
# Reference: https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/keras/preprocessing/image/ImageDataGenerator
datagenerator = ImageDataGenerator(
                    rotation_range = 180,  
                    zoom_range = 0.15, 
                    width_shift_range = 0.10, 
                    height_shift_range = 0.10,
                    horizontal_flip = True,  
                    vertical_flip = True)  

# Compute quantities required for featurewise normalization
datagenerator.fit(x_train)

# Create data iterator for training data
data_itr = datagenerator.flow(x_train, y_train, batch_size=64)

# Train the model
start = time.time()
hist = model.fit(data_itr, epochs=70, validation_data=(x_valid, y_valid), 
                 callbacks=[callback], verbose=True)
end = time.time()

# Print training duration
print('Training took: {0} seconds'.format(round(end-start, 2)))

print('Precision Score: ', round(precision.result().numpy(), 3))

Recall Score: 0.905
Precision Score:  0.919

Observations:¶

  • Good number of convolution layers with more filters were found helpful.
  • Max pooling layers helped amplify important features and eliminate subtle noise.
  • Batch normalization in the feature extractor did not help much and ended up in model over-fitting. However, using batch normalization in the classifier helped. Note: Batch normalization had to be added before the activation layer to be effective.
  • In addition, the kernel initialization used was 'he_normal' and biased were disabled for classifier.
  • Lower learning rate was found useful.
  • The model performed considerably well on the training and validation data. It also demonstrated good classification performance in terms of accuracy, precision and recall scores on the test data.
  • We see a saw-tooth like graph for the validation loss. This could be further smoothen trying different combinations of learning rate and batch size.
  • The confusion matrix showed that the model did fairly well. We see maximum values along the diagonal and minimum values elsewhere indicating significant number of true positives and true negatives.
  • The model is not very confident about 'Loose Silky-bent' and 'Black-grass'. This could be because of lack of training samples for 'Black-grass'.

predicted_labels = []
for idx in test_indexes:
    img = np.asarray(x_test[idx])
    img = (np.expand_dims(img, 0))
    prediction = model.predict(img)
    predicted_labels.append(labels[np.argmax(prediction)])
